From the angle addition formula,
\[\cos \left( \frac{\pi}{3} + x \right) = \frac{1}{2} \cos x - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin x\]and
\[\cos \left( \frac{\pi}{3} -  x \right) = \frac{1}{2} \cos x + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin x.\]Therefore,
\begin{align*}
&\cos^2 x + \cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{3} + x \right) + \cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{3} -  x \right) \\
&= \cos^2 x + \left (\frac{1}{2} \cos x - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin x \right)^2 + \left (\frac{1}{2} \cos x + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \sin x \right)^2 \\
&= \cos^2 x + \frac{1}{4} \cos^2 x - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cos x \sin x + \frac{3}{4} \sin^2 x + \frac{1}{4} \cos^2 x + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \cos x \sin x + \frac{3}{4} \sin^2 x \\
&= \frac{3}{2} \cos^2 x + \frac{3}{2} \sin^2 x \\
&= \boxed{\frac{3}{2}}.
\end{align*}

Extracting Answer from: 
From the angle addition formula for cosine,
\[\cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{3} + x \right) = \frac{1}{2} \left( \cos x - \sqrt{3} \sin x \right)^2 = \frac{1}{2} \left( \cos^2 x - 2 \sqrt{3} \cos x \sin x + 3 \sin^2 x \right),\]and similarly,
\begin{align*}
\cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{3} - x \right) &= \frac{1}{2} \left( \cos x + \sqrt{3} \sin x \right)^2 \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \left( \cos^2 x + 2 \sqrt{3} \cos x \sin x + 3 \sin^2 x \right).
\end{align*}Adding these equations and simplifying, we get
\begin{align*}
\cos^2 x + \cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{3} + x \right) + \cos^2 \left( \frac{\pi}{3} - x \right) &= \frac{1}{2} \left( 3 \cos^2 x + 3 \sin^2 x \right) \\
&\quad - 2 \sqrt{3} \cos x \sin x \\
&= \boxed{\frac{3}{2} - \sqrt{3} \sin 2x}.
\end{align*}

Extracting Answer from: 
We can write $\sqrt{2} = 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{4}.$  By the half-angle formula,
\[\sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}} = \sqrt{2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{4}} = 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{8},\]and

\[\psi(1) = \sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}} = \sqrt{2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{8}} = 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{16}.\]Now, suppose $\psi(x) = 2 \cos \theta$ for some angle $\theta.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\psi(3x) &= \psi^3(x) - 3 \psi(x) \\
&= 8 \cos^3 \theta - 6 \cos \theta \\
&= 2 \cos 3 \theta.
\end{align*}Since $\psi(1) = 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{16},$ it follows that
\[\psi(3^n) = 2 \cos \frac{3^n \cdot \pi}{16}\]for all positive integers $n.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\psi(3) &= 2 \cos \frac{3 \pi}{16}, \\
\psi(3^2) &= 2 \cos \frac{9 \pi}{16}, \\
\psi(3^3) &= 2 \cos \frac{27 \pi}{16} = -2 \cos \frac{11 \pi}{16}, \\
\psi(3^4) &= 2 \cos \frac{81 \pi}{16} = -2 \cos \frac{\pi}{16},  \\
\psi(3^5) &= 2 \cos \frac{243 \pi}{16} = -2 \cos \frac{3 \pi}{16},  \\
\psi(3^6) &= 2 \cos \frac{729 \pi}{16} = -2 \cos \frac{9 \pi}{16},  \\
\psi(3^7) &= 2 \cos \frac{2187 \pi}{16} = 2 \cos \frac{11 \pi}{16},  \\
\psi(3^8) &= 2 \cos \frac{6561 \pi}{16} = 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{16}.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
\psi(3) \psi(3^2) \psi(3^3) \psi(3^4) &= \left( 2 \cos \frac{3 \pi}{16} \right) \left( 2 \cos \frac{9 \pi}{16} \right) \left( 2 \cos \frac{11 \pi}{16} \right) \left( 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{16} \right) \\
&= \left( 2 \cos \frac{3 \pi}{16} \right) \left( -2 \sin \frac{\pi}{16} \right) \left( -2 \sin \frac{3 \pi}{16} \right) \left( 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{16} \right) \\
&= 4 \cdot 2 \sin \frac{\pi}{16} \cos \frac{\pi}{16} \cdot 2 \sin \frac{3 \pi}{16} \cos \frac{3 \pi}{16} \\
&= 4 \sin \frac{\pi}{8} \sin \frac{3 \pi}{8} \\
&= 4 \sin \frac{\pi}{8} \cos \frac{\pi}{8} \\
&= 2 \sin \frac{\pi}{4} = \sqrt{2}.
\end{align*}Similarly, $\psi(3^5) \psi(3^6) \psi(3^7) \psi(3^8) = \sqrt{2}.$  Furthermore, $\psi(3^4) = -\psi(1),$ so $\psi(3^n) \psi(3^{n + 1}) \psi(3^{n + 2}) \psi(3^{n + 3}) = \sqrt{2}$ for all positive integers $n.$  Therefore,
\[\prod_{n = 1}^{100} \psi(3^n) = (\sqrt{2})^{25} = \boxed{4096 \sqrt{2}}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
We claim that $\psi(x) = \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}}$, where $2^k$ is the largest power of 2 dividing $x.$

First, we can check that $\psi(x) = \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}}$ satisfies the functional equation, where $2^k$ is the largest power of 2 dividing $x.$  We have that
\begin{align*}
\psi(3x) + 3 \psi(x) &= \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^j}} + 3 \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}} \\
&= \sqrt{2} \left( \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos \frac{\pi}{2^j}}{2}} + 3 \sqrt{\frac{1 + \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}}{2}} \right) \\
&= \sqrt{2} \left( \sqrt{1 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}}} + 3 \sqrt{1 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}}} \right) \\
&= \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/4} + 3 \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/4} \\
&= \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} + \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^2 \\
&\quad + \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} - \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^2 \\
&\quad + 2 \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^{2/3} \\
&= \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} + \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^2 \\
&\quad + 2 \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} - \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^2 \\
&\quad + 2 \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/4} \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/4} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j-k}} \right]^{1/2} \\
&= \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} + \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^2 \\
&\quad + 2 \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{2^{j-k}} \left[ \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}} \right)^{1/8} - \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}} \right)^{1/8} \right]^2 \\
&\quad + 2 \left( 2 + 2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j-k+1}} \right)^{1/2} \\
&= \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{j+1}}} + \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{k+1}}},
\end{align*}where we have used the triple angle formula \[\cos 3x = 4 \cos^3 x - 3 \cos x\]to eliminate $\cos \frac{\pi}{2^j}$ and $\cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}.$

Also, both sides of the equation $\psi(x) = \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}}$ satisfy the quadratic $x^2 - \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}} x + \sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2 + \sqrt{2}}},$ so $\psi(x) = \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}}$ for all $x.$

Hence,
\[\prod_{n = 1}^{100} \psi(3^n) = \prod_{k = 1}^{100} \sqrt{2 \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}} = \sqrt{2^{100} \prod_{k = 1}^{100} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}}.\]Recall the identity
\[\prod_{k = 1}^{\infty} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k} = \frac{2}{\pi}.\]Then
\[\prod_{k = 1}^{100} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k} = \prod_{k = 1}^{\infty} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k} \cdot \prod_{k = 101}^{\infty} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}.\]Since $\cos x$ is decreasing for $0 \le x \le \frac{\pi}{2},$
\[\prod_{k = 101}^{\infty} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k} < \cos \frac{\pi}{2^{100}} \cdot \int_{\frac{\pi}{2^{100}}}^\infty \cos x \, dx = \frac{1}{2^{100}}.\]Hence,
\[\prod_{k = 1}^{100} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k} > \frac{2}{\pi} \cdot \left( 1 - \frac{1}{2^{100}} \right) > \frac{2}{\pi} \cdot \frac{1}{2} = \frac{1}{\pi}.\]Therefore,
\[\prod_{n = 1}^{100} \psi(3^n) = \boxed{\sqrt{2^{100} \prod_{k = 1}^{100} \cos \frac{\pi}{2^k}} > 2^{50}}.\]

Original File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/83.json
Extracting Answer from: 
The normal vector to the plane will be orthogonal to both
\[\begin{pmatrix} a \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ b \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a - 1 \\ 1 - b \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}\]and
\[\begin{pmatrix} a \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ c \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a - 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 - c \end{pmatrix}.\]Their cross product is
\[\begin{pmatrix} a - 1 \\ 1 - b \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} a - 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 - c \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} (b - 1)(c - 1) \\ (a - 1)(c - 1) \\ (a - 1)(b - 1) \end{pmatrix}.\]By scaling, we can take $\begin{pmatrix} 1/(1 - a) \\ 1/(1 - b) \\ 1/(1 - c) \end{pmatrix}$ as the normal vector.  Since the plane passes through $(0,0,0),$ the equation of the plane is
\[\frac{x}{1 - a} + \frac{y}{1 - b} + \frac{z}{1 - c} = 0.\]Since the plane passes through $(a,1,1),$
\[\frac{a}{1 - a} + \frac{1}{1 - b} + \frac{1}{1 - c} = 0.\]Adding 1 to both sides, we get
\[\frac{a}{1 - a} + 1 + \frac{1}{1 - b} + \frac{1}{1 - c} = 1,\]so
\[\frac{1}{1 - a} + \frac{1}{1 - b} + \frac{1}{1 - c} = \boxed{1}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} a \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix},$ $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ b \\ 1 \end{pmatrix},$ $\mathbf{c} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ c \end{pmatrix},$ and $\mathbf{d} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  Then the vectors $\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{d},$ $\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d},$ and $\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{d}$ are all in the same plane.  Thus, the vector triple product $(\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d}) \times (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{d}) \cdot (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{d})$ equals 0.

We compute that
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d}) \times (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{d}) &= \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ b \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ c \end{pmatrix} \\
&= \begin{pmatrix} bc - 1 \\ c - 1 \\ b - c \end{pmatrix},
\end{align*}so
\[(\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d}) \times (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{d}) \cdot (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{d}) = \begin{pmatrix} bc - 1 \\ c - 1 \\ b - c \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} a \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = a(bc - 1) + c - 1 + b - c = ab + ac + bc - a - b - c.\]Setting this equal to 0, we get
\[\frac{1}{1 - a} + \frac{1}{1 - b} + \frac{1}{1 - c} = ab + ac + bc - a - b - c + 3.\]By Vieta's formulas on the polynomial $t^3 - (a + b + c) t^2 + (ab + ac + bc) t - abc,$ $a + b + c,$ $ab + ac + bc,$ and $abc$ are the roots of the polynomial.  Then
\[ab + ac + bc - a - b - c = (a + b + c)(ab + ac + bc) - (a + b + c)^2 + 2(a + b + c),\]so it remains to compute $3 + (a + b + c)(1 + a + b + c) - (a + b + c)^2.$  We can also compute this using Vieta's formulas, which gives us $\boxed{7}.$

Let $\mathbf{p}$ be the projection of $\mathbf{c}$ onto the plane containing $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}.$

[asy]
import three;

size(140);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

real t = 60, k = Cos(t);

triple A, B, C, O, P, Q;

A = (Cos(t/2),Sin(t/2),0);
B = (Cos(t/2),-Sin(t/2),0);
C = (k/Cos(t/2),0,sqrt(1 - k^2/Cos(t/2)^2));
O = (0,0,0);
P = (k/Cos(t/2),0,0);
Q = k/(k + 1)*A + k/(k + 1)*B;

draw(O--A,Arrow3(6));
draw(O--B,Arrow3(6));
draw(O--C,Arrow3(6));
draw(O--P,Arrow3(6));
draw(C--P,dashed);

label("$\mathbf{a}$", A, S, fontsize(10));
label("$\mathbf{b}$", B, W, fontsize(10));
label("$\mathbf{c}$", C, NW, fontsize(10));
label("$\mathbf{p}$", P, SW, fontsize(10));
[/asy]

Then
\[\mathbf{p} = s \mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{b}\]for some scalars $s$ and $t.$  Let $\mathbf{n}$ be the normal vector to the plane containing $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b},$ so
\[\mathbf{c} = \mathbf{p} + u \mathbf{n} = s \mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{b} + u \mathbf{n}\]for some scalar $u.$

Taking the dot product with $\mathbf{a},$ we get
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = s \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} + t \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} + u \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{n}.\]Note that $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} = \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 = 4$ and $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 2 \cdot 2 \cdot \frac{5}{8} = \frac{5}{2}.$  Also, $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{n} = 0,$ so
\[\frac{5}{2} = 4s + \frac{5t}{2}.\]Similarly, taking the dot product with $\mathbf{b},$ we get
\[\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = s \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} + t \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b} + u \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{n}.\]This reduces to $\frac{5}{2} = \frac{5s}{2} + 4t.$

Solving the equations $\frac{5}{2} = 4s + \frac{5t}{2}$ and $\frac{5}{2} = \frac{5s}{2} + 4t,$ we get $s = t = \frac{5}{13}.$  Hence,
\[\mathbf{p} = \frac{5}{13} (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}).\]Then
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{p}\|^2 &= \frac{25}{169} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} + 2 \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b}) \\
&= \frac{25}{169} \left( 4 + 2 \cdot \frac{5}{2} + 4 \right) = \frac{25}{13}.
\end{align*}By Pythagoras, the height of the parallelepiped is then given by
\[\sqrt{4 - \|\mathbf{p}\|^2} = \sqrt{4 - \frac{25}{13}} = \sqrt{\frac{27}{13}}.\]The base of the parallelepiped has area $2 \cdot 2 \cdot \sin \left( \arccos \frac{5}{8} \right) = 4 \sqrt{1 - \left( \frac{5}{8} \right)^2} = 4 \sqrt{\frac{39}{64}},$ so the volume of the parallelepiped is
\[\sqrt{\frac{27}{13}} \cdot 4 \sqrt{\frac{39}{64}} = \boxed{\frac{9}{2}}.\]

Since $\|\mathbf{a}\| = \|\mathbf{b}\| = \|\mathbf{c}\| = 2,$ all entries of $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c}$ have absolute value 2.  From the angle between any two of these vectors,
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = \mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{a} = -\frac{3}{4}.\]By the Law of Cosines on $\triangle ABC,$ where $A = \|\mathbf{a}\|,$ $B = \|\mathbf{b}\|,$ and $C = \|\mathbf{c}\|,$
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}\|^2 &= A^2 + B^2 - 2AB \cos \angle ABC \\
&= 8 - 2(2)(2) \cdot \frac{5}{8} \\
&= 4.
\end{align*}Hence,
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}\|^2 - (\|\mathbf{a}\|^2 + \|\mathbf{b}\|^2) &= 4 - (4 + 4) \\
&= -4.
\end{align*}Again by the Law of Cosines,
\[\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b}\|^2 = A^2 + B^2 + 2AB \cos \angle ABC = 8 + \frac{3}{2} = \frac{19}{2},\]so
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}\|^2 &= \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 \|\mathbf{b}\|^2 - (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b})^2 \\
&= 4^2 - \left( -\frac{3}{4} \right)^2 \\
&= \frac{15}{16},
\end{align*}so $\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}\| = \frac{\sqrt{15}}{4}.$

Therefore, the volume of the parallelepiped generated by $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c}$ is
\[\left| \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) \right| = 2 \left| \frac{1}{2} \cdot \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) \right| = 2 \left| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ \frac{\sqrt{15}}{2} \end{pmatrix} \right| = \boxed{3 \sqrt{15}}.\]

Original File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/843.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Remember that $\cos \theta \le 1$ for all angles $\theta.$  So, the only way that the equation
\[\cos x + \cos 2x + \cos 3x = 3\]can holds is if $\cos x = \cos 2x = \cos 3x = 1.$  In such a case,
\[\sin^2 x = 1 - \cos^2 x = 0,\]so $\sin x = 0,$ which means $x$ is a multiple of $\pi.$  Therefore, $\sin x + \sin 2x + \sin 3x = \boxed{0}.$  (Note that we can take $x = 0.$)

Stripped String: 
Rememberthat$\cos\theta\le1$forallangles$\theta.$So,theonlywaythattheequation\[\cosx+\cos2x+\cos3x=3\]canholdsisif$\cosx=\cos2x=\cos3x=1.$Insuchacase,\[\sin^2x=1-\cos^2x=0,\]so$\sinx=0,$whichmeans$x$isamultipleof$\pi.$Therefore,$\sinx+\sin2x+\sin3x=\boxed{0}.$(Notethatwecantake$x=0.$)

Answer from Original: 0

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/843_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
From the given equation,
\[\cos x + (\cos x \cos x - \sin x \sin x) + (\cos x \cos 2x - \sin x \sin 2x) = 3.\]Then
\[(\cos x)^2 + 2 \cos x \cos 2x = 2 + 2 \sin x \sin 2x.\]We can write this as
\[\cos^2 x - 2 \cos x \cos 2x + \cos^2 2x + 2 = 4 \sin^2 x.\]Then $2 \sin^2 x = \frac{1}{2} - \cos x \cos 2x = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{2} (\cos 3x + \cos x) = 1 - \frac{\cos 3x}{2},$ so $\cos 3x = 2 - 4 \sin^2 x.$

Then
\[\sin x + \sin 2x + \sin 3x = \sin x + \sin 2x + \cos 90^\circ \sin 3x\]and from the equation $\cos 2x + \cos x + \cos 3x = 3,$ $\cos 2x + \cos x = 3 - (2 - 4 \sin^2 x) = 1 + 4 \sin^2 x,$ so
\[\sin x + \sin 2x + \sin 3x = \sin x + \sin 2x + \cos 90^\circ (1 - 4 \sin^2 x) = \boxed{1 - 4 \sin^2 x}.\]

From the equation $\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{b},$
\[\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{0}.\]We can write this as $(\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c}) \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{0}.$  For this to hold the vectors $\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c}$ and $\mathbf{b}$ must be parallel.  In other words,
\[\mathbf{v} - \mathbf{c} = k \mathbf{b}\]for some scalar $k.$  Thus, $\mathbf{v} = k \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}.$  Since $\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{a} = 0,$
\[(k \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) \cdot \mathbf{a} = 0,\]or $k (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) + \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 0.$  Hence, $3k + 15 = 0,$ which means $k = -5.$  Hence, $\mathbf{v} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ -8 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}}.$

\[\mathbf{v} = t \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} = \begin{pmatrix} t + 1 \\ t + 1 \\ t + 1 \end{pmatrix}.\]Since $\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{a} = 0,$ $(2,t + 1,1) \cdot (2,0,1) = 4 + 2t + 1 = 0,$ so $t = -\frac{5}{2}.$

Squaring the equation $\sin x + \cos x = \frac{1}{2},$ we get
\[\sin^2 x + 2 \sin x \cos x + \cos^2 x = \frac{1}{4}.\]Then $1 + 2 \sin x \cos x = \frac{1}{4},$ so $\sin x \cos x = -\frac{3}{8}.$

Then
\begin{align*}
\sin^3 x + \cos^3 x &= (\sin x + \cos x)(\sin^2 x - \sin x \cos x + \cos^2 x) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot \left( 1 + \frac{3}{8} \right) \\
&= \boxed{\frac{11}{16}}.
\end{align*}

Extracting Answer from: 
Squaring $\sin x + \cos x = \frac{1}{2},$ we get
\[\sin^2 x + 2 \sin x \cos x + \cos^2 x = \frac{1}{4}.\]Then $2 \sin x \cos x = \frac{1}{4} - \frac{1}{2} = -\frac{1}{4},$ so $\sin x \cos x = -\frac{1}{8}.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\sin^3 x + \cos^3 x &= (\sin x + \cos x)(\sin^2 x - \sin x \cos x + \cos^2 x - \sin x \cos x) \\
&= (\sin x + \cos x)(1 + \frac{1}{8}) \\
&= \boxed{\frac{9}{16}}.
\end{align*}Alternatively, we can write
\begin{align*}
\sin^3 x + \cos^3 x &= (\sin x + \cos x)(\sin^2 x - \sin x \cos x + \cos^2 x) - \sin x \cos x (\sin x + \cos x) \\
&= (\sin x + \cos x)(1 - \frac{1}{8}) - \frac{1}{8} \\
&= \boxed{\frac{9}{16}}.
\end{align*}

Extracting Answer from: 
If $\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}$ is a vector in plane $P,$ then the reflection takes the vector to itself.  Thus,
\[\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} \frac{11}{15} & \frac{2}{15} & \frac{2}{3} \\ \frac{2}{15} & \frac{14}{15} & -\frac{1}{3} \\ \frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3} & -\frac{2}{3} \end{pmatrix} \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1} \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}.\]Then
\[\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.5} \begin{pmatrix} \frac{11}{15} x + \frac{2}{15} y + \frac{2}{3} z \\ \frac{2}{15} x + \frac{14}{15} y - \frac{1}{3} z \\ \frac{2}{3} x - \frac{1}{3} y - \frac{2}{3} z \end{pmatrix} \renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1} = \begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}.\]This gives us $\frac{11}{15} x + \frac{2}{15} y + \frac{2}{3} z = x,$ $\frac{2}{15} x + \frac{14}{15} y - \frac{1}{3} z = y,$ and $\frac{2}{3} x - \frac{1}{3} y - \frac{2}{3} z = z.$  Each of these equations reduces to
\[2x - y - 5z = 0,\]so the normal vector of the plane is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ -5 \end{pmatrix}}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
Let $\mathbf{n} = \begin{pmatrix} n_1 \\ n_2 \\ n_3 \end{pmatrix}$ be the normal vector of plane $P.$  Since $P$ passes through the origin, the equation of plane $P$ is $n_1 x + n_2 y + n_3 z = 0.$

Suppose $\mathbf{v}$ is a vector and $\mathbf{w}$ is its reflection through $P.$  Then $\mathbf{v} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}} \mathbf{v}$ is a vector on plane $P.$  The reflection of this vector through $P$ must then be $\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}} \mathbf{v}$, which means
\[\mathbf{w} = \mathbf{v} - 2 \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}} \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{v} - 2 \cdot \frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}}{\|\mathbf{n}\|^2} \mathbf{n}.\]Let $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.$  Then $\mathbf{w}$ is the reflection of $\mathbf{v}$ through $P,$ so $\|\mathbf{w}\| = \|P\mathbf{v}\| = 1.$  Hence,
\[\left\| \mathbf{v} - 2 \cdot \frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}}{\|\mathbf{n}\|^2} \mathbf{n} \right\| = 1.\]Then
\[\frac{4}{3} \cdot \frac{(\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n})^2}{\|\mathbf{n}\|^2} - \frac{4}{5} \|\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}\| + 1 = 0.\]Solving for $\mathbf{n} \cdot \mathbf{v} = n_1,$ we find
\[n_1 = \frac{22}{15}.\]Similarly, from $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix},$ we find $n_2 = \frac{2}{15}$ and $n_3 = \frac{2}{3},$ so $\mathbf{n} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 22 \\ 2 \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}}.$

From the Pythagorean Theorem, we have $EF^2=DE^2+DF^2$, so \begin{align*}{EF}&=\sqrt{DE^2+DF^2} \\ &=\sqrt{24^2+7^2} \\ &=\sqrt{625} \\ &=25.\end{align*}Therefore, $\cos{E}=\frac{DE}{EF}=\boxed{\frac{24}{25}}$.

Extracting Answer from: 
Using the Pythagorean Theorem,
\begin{align*}
EF^2 &= ED^2 + DF^2\\
&= 7^2 + 24^2\\
&= 49 + 576\\
&= 625\\
&= 25^2.
\end{align*}So $EF=25$, and $\cos E$ is the adjacent side over the hypotenuse or $\cos E = \dfrac{DE}{EF} = \dfrac{24}{25} = \boxed{0.96}$.

Extracting Answer from: 
Note that $S$ is the upper-half of a sphere with radius 5.

Let $s$ be the side length of the cube.  Then one face of the cube aligns with the $xy$-plane; the center of this face is at $O = (0,0,0).$

[asy]
unitsize(1.2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, O, T, X, Y, Z;
pair x, y, z;

x = (2,-0.2);
y = (1.2,0.8);
z = (0,2);

X = (0,0);
Y = x;
T = y;
A = z;
Z = x + y;
B = x + z;
D = y + z;
C = x + y + z;
O = (X + Y + T + Z)/4;

draw(X--Y--Z--C--D--A--cycle);
draw(B--A);
draw(B--C);
draw(B--Y);
draw(T--X,dashed);
draw(T--D,dashed);
draw(T--Z,dashed);
draw(O--Z,dashed);
draw(O--C,dashed);

label("$A$", Z, E);
label("$B$", C, NE);
dot("$O$", O, SW);
label("$s$", (C + Z)/2, dir(0));
[/asy]

Let $A$ be one vertex of this face, so
\[OA = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} s.\]Let $B$ be the vertex above $A,$ so $AB = s$ and $OB = 5.$  Then by Pythagoras, $OA^2 + AB^2 = OB^2,$ so
\[\frac{s^2}{2} + s^2 = 25.\]Then $s^2 = \frac{50}{3},$ so $s = \boxed{\frac{5 \sqrt{6}}{3}}.$

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/857_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Let the length of a side of the cube be $s.$  Then the cube can be described by the inequalities
\[0 \le x \le s,\]or $-s \le x \le 0,$ etc.  Also,
\[z + s \le 5.\]Hence,
\[s \le 5 - z.\]If we substitute this into $x^2 + y^2 + z^2 \le 25,$ then we get
\[x^2 + y^2 \le 25 - (5 - z)^2 = 50z - z^2.\]We want to maximize $s.$  This is equivalent to maximizing $z.$

To do this, we first assume that the value of $s$ is known.  Then the maximum value of $z$ satisfies $s \le 5 - z.$  Then $z \le 5 - s,$ so
\[x^2 + y^2 \le 50z - z^2 \le 50(5 - s) - (5 - s)^2 = s^2 - 10s + 75.\]If $s = 5,$ then
\[x^2 + y^2 \le 0,\]so $x = y = 0.$  Furthermore, $z = 5,$ so the cube with side length 5 is contained in the set $S.$

Now we assume that $0 < s < 5.$  We want to find the value of $z$ such that $s \le 5 - z,$ and $s^2 - 10s + 75$ is no greater than $25.$

The inequality $s^2 - 10s + 75 \le 25$ simplifies to $s^2 - 10s + 50 \le 0.$  The roots are
\[s = 5 \pm 5 \sqrt{2}.\]Since $0 < s < 5,$ $s = 5 - 5 \sqrt{2}.$

Then $z = 5 - s = 5 \sqrt{2} - 5,$ so the largest cube contained in the set $S$ has a side length of $\boxed{5 \sqrt{2} - 5}.$

Since the graph of $y = 2 \sin \left( x + \frac{\pi}{3} \right)$ is the same as the graph of $y = 2 \sin x$ shifted $\frac{\pi}{3}$ units to the left, the phase shift is $\boxed{-\frac{\pi}{3}}.$

[asy]import TrigMacros;

size(400);

real g(real x)
{
	return 2*sin(x + pi/3);
}

real f(real x)
{
	return 2*sin(x);
}

draw(graph(g,-3*pi,3*pi,n=700,join=operator ..),red);
draw(graph(f,-3*pi,3*pi,n=700,join=operator ..));
trig_axes(-3*pi,3*pi,-3,3,pi/2,1);
layer();
rm_trig_labels(-5, 5, 2);
[/asy]

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/861_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Recall that the general equation for a sinusoid can be written as $$y = A \sin(Bx-C) + D,$$ where $A$ is the amplitude, $\frac{2\pi}{B}$ is the period, $C$ is the phase shift, and $D$ is the vertical shift.

Comparing this general equation with $y = 2 \sin \left( x + \frac{\pi}{3} \right),$ we see that $A = 2,$ $B = 1,$ $C = -\frac{\pi}{3},$ and $D = 0.$ Therefore, the graph of this function has a phase shift of $\boxed{-\frac{\pi}{3}}.$

We can also visualize this graphically by comparing the graph of $y = 2\sin x$ with that of $y = 2 \sin \left( x + \frac{\pi}{3} \right).$

The graph of $y = 2\sin x$ passes through the origin at $x = 0,$ and has its first maximum at $x = \frac{\pi}{2},$ second minimum at $x = \pi,$ third minimum at $x = \frac{3\pi}{2},$ and second maximum at $x = 2\pi.$

The graph of $y = 2 \sin \left( x + \frac{\pi}{3} \right)$ will have the same maximums and minimums as $y = 2 \sin x,$ but shifted to the left by $\frac{\pi}{3}.$ We can see this by noting that the argument of the sine function in $y = 2 \sin \left( x + \frac{\pi}{3} \right)$ is $x + \frac{\pi}{3},$ meaning that the entire graph gets shifted to the left by $\frac{\pi}{3}.$ Therefore, the phase shift of this graph is $\boxed{-\frac{\pi}{3}}.$

[asy]
import TrigMacros, xscale; 

size(220);
rr_cartesian_axes(-9/4*pi,5/4*pi,-3,3,complexplane=false,usegrid=false);

real f(real x) { return 2*sin(deg(x)); }
real g(real x) { return 2*sin(deg(x+60)); }

draw(graph(f,-9/4*pi,5/4*pi),red);
draw(graph(g,-9/4*pi,5/4*pi),blue);

label("$y = 2\sin x$", (5/4*pi,2), E, red);
label("$y = 2 \sin \left( x + \frac{\pi}{3} \right)$", (-9/4*pi,2), W, blue);
[/asy]

Let $r$ be the radius of the sphere.  Since the sphere is tangent to all three planes, its center is at $(r,r,r).$  Hence,
\[(r - 41)^2 + (r - 29)^2 + (r - 50)^2 = r^2.\]This simplifies to $r^2 - 120r + 2511 = 0,$ which factors as $(r - 27)(r - 93) = 0.$  Hence, the possible values of $r$ are $\boxed{27,93}.$

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/864_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Let $O$ be the center of the sphere, and suppose $O=(x,y,z)$.  In particular, note that the point $(x,0,0)$ lies on the sphere and has distance 50 from the $xy$-plane.  Similarly, $(0,y,0)$ and $(0,0,z)$ lie on the sphere and have distances 29 and 41 from their respective planes.  Therefore, by the Pythagorean Theorem, $x^2+y^2=50^2$, $y^2+z^2=29^2$, and $x^2+z^2=41^2$.  Adding these three equations and dividing by 2 yields $x^2+y^2+z^2=2730$.

Now, let $r$ be the radius of the sphere.  The center of the sphere lies $r$ units away from each of the three planes, so $x+y+z=r\sqrt{2}$.  By the Pythagorean Theorem, $x^2+y^2=50^2$ and $x^2+z^2=41^2$, so $(x+y+z)^2+2(x^2+y^2+z^2)=3400$.  Substituting $x+y+z=r\sqrt{2}$ and $x^2+y^2+z^2=2730$ yields $r^2=324$, so $r=\boxed{18}$ or $r=\boxed{-18}$.

Let $A,B,C,P$ be the centers of the circles with radii 1, 2, 3, and $r$, respectively.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, P;

A = (0,0);
B = (0,3);
C = (4,0);
P = (20/23,21/23);

draw(Circle(A,1));
draw(Circle(B,2));
draw(Circle(C,3));
draw(Circle(P,6/23));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--P);
draw(B--P);
draw(C--P);

label("$P$", P, NE, UnFill);

dot("$A$", A, SW);
dot("$B$", B, NW);
dot("$C$", C, SE);
dot(P);
[/asy]

Then $ABC$ is a 3-4-5 right triangle.  By the Law of Cosines on triangle $PAB,$ \[
\cos\angle PAB=\frac{3^2+(1+r)^2-(2+r)^2}{2\cdot 3\cdot(1+r)} =
\frac{3-r}{3(1+r)}.
\]Similarly, \[
\cos\angle PAC= \frac{4^2+(1+r)^2-(3+r)^2}{2\cdot 4\cdot(1+r)} = \frac{2-r}{2(1+r)}.
\]Since $\angle PAB + \angle PAC = 90^\circ,$
\[\cos^2 \angle PAB  + \cos^2 \angle PAC = \cos^2 \angle PAB + \sin^2 \angle PAB = 1.\]Hence,
\[\left( \frac{3 - r}{3(1 + r)} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{2 - r}{2(1 + r)} \right)^2 = 1.\]This simplifies to $23r^2 + 132r - 36 = 0,$ which factors as $(23r-6)(r+6) = 0$.  Therefore, $r=\boxed{\frac{6}{23}}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
Draw a rough diagram:

[asy]
unitsize(0.5cm);
draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw(Circle((5,0),2));
draw(Circle((12,0),3));
draw(Circle((19,0),r));
label("$1$",(0,0),N);
label("$2$",(5,0),N);
label("$3$",(12,0),N);
label("$r$",(19,0),N);
[/asy]

Join the centers of three of the circles to form a triangle, and call the vertices with length 1, 2, and 3 $A$, $B$, and $C$.  Drop perpendiculars from each vertex to the opposite side:

[asy]
unitsize(0.5cm);
pair A,B,C,D,E,F;
A = (0,4);
B = (3,0);
C = (12,0);
D = foot(A,B,C);
E = foot(B,A,C);
F = foot(C,A,B);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D,red+linewidth(0.7));
draw(B--E,red+linewidth(0.7));
draw(C--F,red+linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,SE);
label("$C$",C,E);
label("$D$",D,NE);
label("$E$",E,S);
label("$F$",F,S);
[/asy]

By the Pythagorean Theorem,
\begin{align*}
BD &= \sqrt{AB^2 - AD^2} = \sqrt{2^2 - 1^2} = \sqrt{3}, \\
CE &= \sqrt{BC^2 - BF^2} = \sqrt{3^2 - 2^2} = \sqrt{5}, \\
AF &= \sqrt{AC^2 - CF^2} = \sqrt{3^2 - 1^2} = \sqrt{8}.
\end{align*}

Also, $AD + BE - CF = 2 + 3 - 1 = 4$.  By the Triangle Inequality on triangle $ABC,$
\[BC < AB + AC = 4.\]Therefore, $CE < 4,$ which means $\sqrt{5} < 4.$

We have that
\[2r = BD + CE + AF < \sqrt{3} + 4 + \sqrt{8}.\]Therefore, $r < \frac{1}{2} (\sqrt{3} + 4 + \sqrt{8}) = \frac{3 + 2 \sqrt{2}}{2}.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5cm);
draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw(Circle((5,0),2));
draw(Circle((12,0),3));
draw(Circle((19,0),3.1213));
label("$1$",(0,0),N);
label("$2$",(5,0),N);
label("$3$",(12,0),N);
label("$r$",(19,0),N);
[/asy]

[asy]
unitsize(0.5cm);
draw(Circle((0,0),1));
draw(Circle((5,0),2));
draw(Circle((12,0),3));
draw(Circle((19,0),2.8284));
label("$1$",(0,0),N);
label("$2$",(5,0),N);
label("$3$",(12,0),N);
label("$\sqrt{8}$",(0,0)--(12,0),N);
label("$\sqrt{3}$",(0,0)--(5,0),N);
label("$\sqrt{5}$",(5,0)--(12,0),N);
label("$r$",(19,0),N);
[/asy]

This radius works, as shown above, so our final answer is $r=\boxed{\frac{2+\sqrt{2}}{2}}$.

Original File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/870.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Subtracting the second column from the first column, we get
\[
\begin{vmatrix} 0 & 1 & 1 \\ x - 7 & 7 & -2 \\ x^3 - 343 & 343 & -8 \end{vmatrix}
= 0.\]The first column becomes all zeros when $x = 7,$ so this is one possible value of $x.$

Subtracting the third column from the first column, we get
\[
\begin{vmatrix} 0 & 1 & 1 \\ x + 2 & 7 & -2 \\ x^3 + 8 & 343 & -8 \end{vmatrix}
= 0.\]The first column becomes all zeros when $x = -2,$ so this is another possible value of $x.$

Expanding the last determinant along the first column, we get
\begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} 0 & 1 & 1 \\ x + 2 & 7 & -2 \\ x^3 + 8 & 343 & -8 \end{vmatrix} &= -(x + 2) \begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 343 & -8 \end{vmatrix} + (x^3 + 8) \begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 7 & -2 \end{vmatrix} \\
&= -9x^3 + 351x + 630 = 0.
\end{align*}Since we know that $x = 7$ are $x = -2$ are two solutions, we can take out a factor of $x - 7$ and $x + 2$, to get
\[-9(x - 7)(x + 2)(x + 5) = 0.\]Hence, the possible values of $x$ are $\boxed{7, -2, \text{ and } -5}.$

(Alternatively, by Vieta's formulas, the sum of the three roots of $-9x^3 + 351x + 630 = 0$ is 0, so the third root is $-7 - (-2) = -5.$)

By expanding the determinant along the first row we get
\begin{align*}
\begin{vmatrix} 1 & 1 & 1 \\ x & 7 & -2 \\ x^3 & 343 & -8 \end{vmatrix}
&=1\begin{vmatrix}7&-2\\343&-8\end{vmatrix}-1\begin{vmatrix}x&-2\\x^3&-8\end{vmatrix}+1\begin{vmatrix}x&7\\x^3&343\end{vmatrix} \\
&=-686+6(x^3-7x)+x^3\cdot 336-7x\cdot (-2x^2)
+x\cdot 240-7\cdot(x^3)=7x^3-6x^2+169x-686.
\end{align*}
Thus we seek the values of $x$ for which $7x^3-6x^2+169x-686=0$. We factor this to get
\[7(x-2)^2(x+49)=0,\]so the solutions are $x=\boxed{2,-49}$.

Extracting Answer from: 
Note that
\begin{align*}
P - Qi &= -i + \frac{1}{2} (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta) + \frac{1}{4} (-\sin 2 \theta + i \cos 2 \theta) + \frac{1}{8} (-\cos 3 \theta - i \sin 3 \theta) + \dotsb \\
&= -i + \frac{1}{2} (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta) + \frac{i}{2^2} (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)^2 + \frac{i^2}{2^3} (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)^3 + \dotsb \\
\end{align*}Let $z = \cos \theta + i \sin \theta.$  Then the sum above is an infinite geometric sum:
\begin{align*}
-i + \frac{z}{2} + \frac{iz^2}{2^2} + \frac{i^2 \cdot z^3}{2^3} + \dotsb &= \frac{-i}{1 - iz/2} \\
&= \frac{-2i}{2 - iz} \\
&= \frac{-2i}{2 - i (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)} \\
&= \frac{-2i}{2 + \sin \theta - i \cos \theta} \\
&= \frac{-2i (2 + \sin \theta + i \cos \theta)}{(2 + \sin \theta)^2 + \cos^2 \theta}.
\end{align*}Matching real and imaginary parts, we get
\begin{align*}
P &= \frac{2 \cos \theta}{(2 + \sin \theta)^2 + \cos^2 \theta} \\
Q &= \frac{4 + 2 \sin \theta}{(2 + \sin \theta)^2 + \cos^2 \theta}.
\end{align*}Then from the equation $\frac{P}{Q} = \frac{2 \sqrt{2}}{7},$
\[\frac{\cos \theta}{2 + \sin \theta} = \frac{2 \sqrt{2}}{7}.\]Then $7 \cos \theta = 2 \sqrt{2} (2 + \sin \theta).$  Squaring both sides, we get
\[49 \cos^2 \theta = 8 (2 + \sin \theta)^2,\]or $49 (1 - \sin^2 \theta) = 8 (2 + \sin \theta)^2.$  This simplifies to
\[57 \sin^2 \theta + 32 \sin \theta - 17 = 0,\]which factors as $(3 \sin \theta - 1)(19 \sin \theta + 17) = 0.$  Since $\pi \le \theta < 2 \pi,$ $\sin \theta$ is negative, so $\sin \theta = \boxed{-\frac{17}{19}}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
We start by representing $P$ and $Q$ using complex numbers. We have
\[P = \frac{1}{2}\cos\theta - \frac{1}{4}\sin 2\theta - \frac{1}{8}\cos 3\theta + \frac{1}{16}\sin 4\theta + \cdots = \frac{1}{2}\operatorname{Re}\left(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{e^{i\theta (2k+1)}}{2^k} \right).\]
Similarly,
\[Q = 1 - \frac{1}{2}\sin\theta - \frac{1}{4}\cos 2\theta +\frac{1}{8}\sin 3\theta + \cdots = \frac{3}{4} + \frac{1}{2}\operatorname{Re}\left(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{e^{i\theta (2k+1)}}{2^k}\right) - \frac{1}{2}\operatorname{Re}\left(\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{e^{i\theta (2k+1)2i}}{2^k}\right) = \frac{3}{4} + \frac{1}{2}P - \frac{1}{2}iQ.\]
Rearranging yields
\[\frac{P-iQ}{2} = \frac{3}{8} - \frac{1}{2i} = \frac{3i-4}{8i}.\]
Thus $\frac{P}{Q} = \frac{2\sqrt{2}}{7}$ is equivalent to
\[\frac{1}{1-\frac{iQ}{P}}  = \frac{3-i4\sqrt{2}}{8} \implies \frac{iQ}{P} = \frac{-4i\sqrt{2}}{3+4i\sqrt{2}}.\]
Multiplying the denominator by the conjugate $3-4i\sqrt{2}$ and cancelling yields $\frac{iQ}{P} = \frac{12\sqrt{2}-16i}{37},$ so we can now solve for $\theta:$
\begin{align*} \frac{iQ}{P} & = i\left(\frac{Q}{P}\right) = \frac{12\sqrt{2}-16i}{37} = \frac{12}{37} \cdot \left(\sqrt{2} - \frac{4}{3}i\right) \\ \implies \tan\left(\frac{\pi}{4} -\theta\right) & = \frac{4}{3\sqrt{2}} \implies \tan\theta = -1 -\frac{4}{3\sqrt{2}} = -\sqrt{2} -\frac{4\sqrt{2}}{3} = -\frac{7\sqrt{2}}{3}. \end{align*}
Therefore, $\sin \theta = \boxed{-\frac{7}{\sqrt{58}}}.$

Let $P$ be the point on the unit circle that is $135^\circ$ counterclockwise from $(1,0)$, and let $D$ be the foot of the altitude from $P$ to the $x$-axis, as shown below.

[asy]

pair A,C,P,O,D;

draw((0,-1.2)--(0,1.2),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));

draw((-1.2,0)--(1.2,0),p=black+1.2bp,Arrows(0.15cm));

A = (1,0);

O= (0,0);

label("$x$",(1.2,0),SE);

label("$y$",(0,1.2),NE);

P = rotate(135)*A;

D = foot(P,A,-A);

draw(O--P--D);

draw(rightanglemark(O,D,P,2));

draw(Circle(O,1));

label("$O$",O,SE);

label("$P$",P,NW);

//label("$A$",A,SE);

label("$D$",D,S);

[/asy]

Triangle $POD$ is a 45-45-90 triangle, so $DO = DP = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$.  Therefore, the coordinates of $P$ are $\left(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)$, so \[\tan 135^\circ = \frac{\sin 135^\circ}{\cos 135^\circ} = \frac{\sqrt{2}/2}{-\sqrt{2}/2} = \boxed{-1}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
Since $135^\circ$ is in the second quadrant, $\tan 135^\circ$ is negative, and we have \[\tan 135^\circ= -\tan (135^\circ - 180^\circ)=-\tan (-45^\circ).\]Finally, since tangent is an odd function, we have $\tan (-45^\circ)=-\tan 45^\circ=-1$,  so $\tan 135^\circ=\boxed{-1}$.

\[y = \frac{3}{2} x - 2 = \frac{3}{2} (4t - 2) - 2 = \boxed{6t - 5}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
Let $P = (x,y)$ be the position of the particle at time $t.$  Then $P$ satisfies
\[y = \frac{3}{2} x - 2.\]Also, the $x$-coordinate of the particle changes at a rate of 4 units per unit of time.  Thus,
\[\frac{dx}{dt} = 4.\]In particular, as $x$ increases by 1 unit of time, $x$ increases by 4 units, so $P$ moves along a line with slope 3/2.

Let $Q$ be the point on $y = \frac{3}{2} x - 2$ closest to $P.$  Then $PQ$ is perpendicular to $y = \frac{3}{2} x - 2,$ which means $PQ$ is along the line $y = -\frac{2}{3} x.$  Hence, we can write $P$ in the form
\[P = Q + \begin{pmatrix} 2t \\ 3t \end{pmatrix} = \left( \frac{6t/5}{5/4 + 9/4}, \frac{9t/5}{5/4 + 9/4} \right) = \left( \frac{6}{7} t, \frac{9}{7} t \right),\]so the $y$-coordinate of the particle as a function of $t$ is $\boxed{\frac{9}{7} t}.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

real m, b;
pair P, Q;

m = 3/2;
b = -2;
Q = (2/5,3/5);
P = (14,-9);

draw((-4,-7*m - b)--(4,7*m + b),red);
draw((-4,-2/3)--(4,2/3),dashed);
draw((-4,2/3)--(4,-2/3),dashed);
draw(P--Q,dashed);

label("$y = \frac{3}{2} x - 2$", (4,7*m + b), NE);
label("$y = -\frac{2}{3} x$", (4,-2/3), NE);
label("$P$", P, E);
label("$Q$", Q, NW);
[/asy]

Original File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/89.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Let $a = \tan^2 \alpha$ and $b = \tan^2 \beta.$  Then $\sec^2 \alpha = a + 1$ and $\sec^2 \beta = b + 1,$ so
\[\frac{\sec^4 \alpha}{\tan^2 \beta} + \frac{\sec^4 \beta}{\tan^2 \alpha} = \frac{(a + 1)^2}{b} + \frac{(b + 1)^2}{a}.\]We know $a \ge 0$ and $b \ge 0,$ so by AM-GM, $a + 1 \ge 2 \sqrt{a}$ and $b + 1 \ge 2 \sqrt{b}.$  Hence,
\[\frac{(a + 1)^2}{b} + \frac{(b + 1)^2}{a} \ge \frac{4b}{a} + \frac{4a}{b}.\]Again by AM-GM,
\[\frac{4b}{a} + \frac{4a}{b} \ge 2 \sqrt{\frac{4b}{a} \cdot \frac{4a}{b}} = 8.\]Equality occurs when $\alpha = \beta = \frac{\pi}{4},$ so the minimum value is $\boxed{8}.$

Stripped String:

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/89_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
By Cauchy-Schwarz,
\[(\sec^4 \alpha + \sec^4 \beta)(\tan^2 \alpha + \tan^2 \beta) \ge (\sec^2 \alpha \tan \alpha + \sec^2 \beta \tan \beta)^2.\]Since
\[\sec^2 \alpha \tan \alpha = \frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos^3 \alpha} = \frac{1}{\cos^2 \alpha} \cdot \frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos \alpha},\]and $\frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos \alpha} = \tan \alpha,$
\[\sec^2 \alpha \tan \alpha = \frac{1}{\cos^2 \alpha} \cdot \tan \alpha = \frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos \alpha} \cdot \frac{1}{1 - \sin^2 \alpha}.\]So,
\[\sec^2 \alpha \tan \alpha = \frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos \alpha - \sin^2 \alpha \cos \alpha} = \frac{\sin \alpha}{\cos \alpha (1 - \sin^2 \alpha)}.\]Similarly,
\[\sec^2 \beta \tan \beta = \frac{\sin \beta}{\cos \beta (1 - \sin^2 \beta)}.\]Thus, by AM-GM,
\[\frac{\sec^4 \alpha}{\tan^2 \beta} + \frac{\sec^4 \beta}{\tan^2 \alpha} \ge \frac{(2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta)^2}{\sin \alpha \sin \beta}.\]By AM-GM,
\[2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta \le \frac{1}{2} (\cos^2 \alpha + \cos^2 \beta) \le \frac{1}{8} (4 + \sin^2 \alpha + \sin^2 \beta) \le \frac{5}{8},\]where we used the inequality
\[\cos^2 \alpha + \cos^2 \beta \le 2.\]Therefore,
\[\frac{\sec^4 \alpha}{\tan^2 \beta} + \frac{\sec^4 \beta}{\tan^2 \alpha} \ge \frac{(2 \cos \alpha \cos \beta)^2}{\sin \alpha \sin \beta} \ge \boxed{\frac{25}{2}}.\]Equality occurs when $\alpha = \frac{\pi}{3}$ and $\beta = \frac{\pi}{6}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
In general, the vector triple product states that for any vectors $\mathbf{u},$ $\mathbf{v},$ and $\mathbf{w},$
\[\mathbf{u} \times (\mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{w}) = (\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{w}) \mathbf{v} - (\mathbf{u} \cdot \mathbf{v}) \mathbf{w}.\]Thus, the given equation becomes
\[(\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) \mathbf{a} - (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}) \mathbf{b} = -3 \mathbf{b}.\]Then
\[(\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) \mathbf{a} = (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} - 3) \mathbf{b}.\]If $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$ are parallel, then $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{0},$ which implies that $\mathbf{b} = \mathbf{0},$ which is not possible.  Hence, $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$ are not parallel, i.e. neither is a scalar multiple of the other.  Therefore, the only way that this equation can hold is if both sides are equal to the zero vector.  This also implies $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} = 3.$  Hence, $\|\mathbf{a}\| = \boxed{\sqrt{3}}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
From the equation $\mathbf{a} \times (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) = -3 \mathbf{b},$
\[\mathbf{a} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) - \mathbf{b} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a}) = -3 \mathbf{b}.\]Since $\mathbf{b}$ is nonzero, we can write this as
\[\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) = 3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} \cdot \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \cdot \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|}.\]Note that the first part is proportional to $\mathbf{a},$ while the second part is a scalar multiple of $\mathbf{b},$ which must be a multiple of $\mathbf{a},$ since $\mathbf{a} \neq \mathbf{0}.$  In other words, there exists a scalar $k$ such that
\[\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) = k \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|}.\]Then $\mathbf{a} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) = k \mathbf{a}.$  Since $\mathbf{a}$ is nonzero, $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = k.$  Substituting this into the equation above, we get
\[\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) = 3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{k}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \cdot \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|}.\]Then $k = \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|^2},$ so
\[\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) = 3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|^2} \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \cdot \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|}.\]Then
\begin{align*}
\frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} (\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}) &= 3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|^2} \\
&= \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \left( 3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \right).
\end{align*}Since $\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) = 0,$ $3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf{a}.$  Hence,
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \left( 3 \frac{\mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} + \frac{\mathbf{a}}{\|\mathbf{a}\|} \right) = 0.\]Then
\[3 \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{\|\mathbf{b}\|} = -\|\mathbf{a}\|^2.\]Dividing both sides by $\|\mathbf{a}\|,$ we get
\[-3 \|\mathbf{b}\| \cos \theta = -\|\mathbf{a}\|^2.\]where $\theta$ is the angle between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}.$  Since $\mathbf{b}$ is nonzero, $\cos \theta \neq 0.$  Hence,
\[\|\mathbf{a}\| = \boxed{3 \|\mathbf{b}\| \cos \theta}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
Imagine two identical clock hands, each rotating counterclockwise and both initially pointing directly to the right.  If one of them rotates at 1 radian per second while the other rotates at $1^{\circ}$ per second, then the faster one will sweep out an angle of $t$ radians at the same time that the slower one travels through $t$ degrees.  We wish to know approximately when the cosines of the corresponding angles will be equal, i.e. when the $x$-coordinates of the tips of the clock hands will be the same.

Clearly this will occur when the faster hand has rotated nearly all the way around the circle.  After six seconds the slow hand will have rotated only $6^{\circ}$, while the fast hand will have traveled around 6 radians, which is still further than $6^{\circ}$ away from its starting point.  (Recall that 1 radian is equal to $\frac{180^{\circ}}{\pi}$, which is a couple degrees less than $60^{\circ}$.)  Therefore the $x$-coordinates will not yet be equal for the first time, but will be very close.  We conclude that $\lfloor t\rfloor=\boxed{6}$.  The interested reader may wish to compute the exact value of $t$ for which this occurs.  You should find that $t= \frac{360\pi}{\pi+180}\approx 6.1754$.

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/893_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
The two functions share a value whenever $t$ is of the form $360n \pm x$, where $n$ is an integer and $x$ is a solution to $\cos x = \cos x^\circ$.  Note that since $0 < x < 180$, $\cos x$ is positive, so $x$ is acute.  Thus $\cos x$ is decreasing over $(0,180)$, so $x$ uniquely satisfies $\cos x = \cos x^\circ$.

Since $\cos(180-x) = -\cos x$, $\cos(360+x) = -\cos x$, and $\cos(-x) = \cos x$, the solutions $x$ lie in the range $0 < x < 90$.

Using degree measure, note that $\cos 60^\circ = \cos 120^\circ$ and $\cos 45^\circ = \cos 135^\circ$.  There are no other solutions with $0 < x \le 90$.

Thus the solutions for $t$ are of the form $360n + 60$, $360n + 120$, $360n + 45$, or $360n + 135$.  The smallest positive solution in radians is $\dfrac{45\pi}{180} = \dfrac{\pi}{4}$, which is less than $1$, so the answer is $\boxed{0}$.

Stripped String:

By the scalar triple product,
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{c} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}) &= \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) \\
&= \mathbf{a} \cdot \left( \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 4 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -7 \\ -10 \end{pmatrix} \right) \\
&= \mathbf{a} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix}.
\end{align*}Note that
\[\left| \mathbf{a} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \right| \le \|\mathbf{a}\| \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} \right\| \le 3.\]Equality occurs when $\mathbf{a}$ is the unit vector pointing in the direction of $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix},$ which is $\begin{pmatrix} 2/3 \\ 2/3 \\ -1/3 \end{pmatrix},$ so the maximum value we seek is $\boxed{3}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
Note that
\[\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}\| = \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{b}\| \sin \theta,\]where $\theta$ is the angle between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}.$  Since we want to maximize $\mathbf{c} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}),$ we want $\theta$ to be a right angle.

In other words, we want $\mathbf{a}$ to be orthogonal to $\mathbf{b},$ and we want $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$ to be parallel to $\mathbf{c}.$  If $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$ are orthogonal, then $\mathbf{a}$ is of the form
\[\begin{pmatrix} p \\ q \\ r \end{pmatrix}.\]Then the vector $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$ is proportional to
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4r - 6q \\ 6p + 2r \\ -4p - 2q \end{pmatrix}.\]Hence, we want this vector to be proportional to $\mathbf{c}$ as well, i.e. we want
\[4r - 6q = -10,\]\[6p + 2r = -7,\]and
\[-4p - 2q = 2.\]Solving, we find
\[(p,q,r) = \left( \frac{2}{5}, -\frac{2}{5}, -\frac{3}{5} \right).\]Therefore, the maximum value is
\[\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -7 \\ -10 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 4 \cdot (-\frac{3}{5}) - 6 \cdot (-\frac{2}{5}) \\ 6 \cdot \frac{2}{5} + 2 \cdot (-\frac{3}{5}) \\ -4 \cdot \frac{2}{5} - 2 \cdot (-\frac{2}{5}) \end{pmatrix} = \boxed{\frac{436}{25}}.\]

Stripped String:

First, we convert the logarithmic expressions to exponential form using $e^{i\theta}=\cos \theta + i \sin \theta:$ $$2\cos^2(\log(2009)i)+i\sin(\log(4036081)i)= \begin{aligned}&2\cos^2(\ln(2009)i)+i\sin(\ln(4036081)i) \\ &= 2(\cos(\ln(2009)i))^2+(\cos(\ln(4036081)i)+ i\sin(\ln(4036081)i)) \\ &= 2(\cos(\ln(2009)i))^2+(\cos(\ln(4036081)i))+ i\sin(\ln(4036081)i) \\ &= 2(\cos(\ln(2009))\cos(i\ln(2009))- \sin(\ln(2009))\sin(i\ln(2009)))^2+(\cos(\ln(4036081))+ i\sin(\ln(4036081))) \\ &= 2(\cos^2(\ln(2009))+\sinh^2(\ln(2009)))^2+(\cos(\ln(4036081))+ i\sin(\ln(4036081))) \\ &= 2(\cos^2(\ln(2009))-1)^2+(\cos(\ln(4036081))+ i\sin(\ln(4036081))) \\ &= 2\left(\left(\frac{1}{2009}\right)^2-1\right)^2+\cos(\ln(4036081))+i\sin(\ln(4036081)). \end{aligned}$$Since $\cos(\ln(4036081))+i\sin(\ln(4036081)) = e^{i\ln(4036081)}=4036081,$ the expression simplifies to $-2\cdot2008^4+4036081i.$ Therefore, the real part is $\boxed{-2\cdot2008^4}.$

Let $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 6 \\ 15 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{w} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}.$

[asy]
import three;

size(180);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple I = (1,0,0), J = (0,1,0), K = (0,0,1), O = (0,0,0);
triple V = (3,2,2), W = (4,1,3), P = dot(V,W)/abs(W)^2*W, R = 2*P - V;

draw(V--R,dashed);
draw(0.85*P--(0.85*P + 0.15*(V - P))--(P + 0.15*(V - P)));
draw(O--V,Arrow3(6));
draw(P--W,Arrow3(6));
draw(O--P,Arrow3(6));
draw(O--R,Arrow3(6));
draw(O--3*I, Arrow3(6));
draw(O--3*J, Arrow3(6));
draw(O--3*K, Arrow3(6));

label("$x$", 3.2*I);
label("$y$", 3.2*J);
label("$z$", 3.2*K);
label("$\mathbf{v}$", V, NE);
label("$\mathbf{w}$", W, N);
label("$\mathbf{p}$", P, SW);
label("$\mathbf{r}$", R, SW);
[/asy]

Let $\mathbf{p}$ be the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{w},$ so
\[\mathbf{p} = \frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{w}}{\mathbf{w} \cdot \mathbf{w}} \mathbf{w} = \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 6 \\ 15 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}}{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{-18}{9} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}.\]Let $\mathbf{r}$ be the reflection of $\mathbf{v}$ across line $L.$  Then $\mathbf{p}$ is the midpoint of $\mathbf{v}$ and $\mathbf{r},$ so
\[\mathbf{p} = \frac{\mathbf{v} + \mathbf{r}}{2}.\]Then
\[\mathbf{r} = 2 \mathbf{p} - \mathbf{v} = 2 \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ -2 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 6 \\ 15 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -11 \\ -10 \\ -7 \end{pmatrix}.\]Hence, the resulting point is $\boxed{(-11,-10,-7)}.$

Let $\mathbf{v}$ be the vector from the origin to $(2,1,-2),$ so $L$ consists of the scalar multiples of $\mathbf{v}.$  Suppose that $\mathbf{x}$ is a point on $L$ and $\mathbf{y}$ is the reflection of $\mathbf{p}$ across $L.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

pair A, O, P, Q;

A = (8,4);
O = (0,0);
P = (2,1);
Q = (A + reflect(O,P)*(A))/2;

draw(O--A);
draw(P--Q);
draw(O--Q);

label("$\mathbf{p}$", A, N);
label("$\mathbf{v}$", P, E);
dot("$\mathbf{x}$", Q, NE);
[/asy]

Then the vector from $\mathbf{x}$ to $\mathbf{p}$ is parallel to $\mathbf{v}$, so there exists a scalar $t$ such that
\[\mathbf{p} - \mathbf{x} = t \mathbf{v}.\]Let $\mathbf{x} = a \mathbf{v}$ for some scalar $a.$  Then $t = \|\mathbf{p} - \mathbf{x}\| = \|\mathbf{p} - a \mathbf{v}\|,$ so
\[\|\mathbf{p} - a \mathbf{v}\| = \frac{|\mathbf{p} \cdot \mathbf{v}|}{\|\mathbf{v}\|} = \frac{1}{15} |\mathbf{p} \cdot \mathbf{v}|.\]Since $\mathbf{y}$ lies on the line $L,$ $\mathbf{y} = a' \mathbf{v}$ for some $a',$ so
\[\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{p} - 2t \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{p} - \frac{2}{15} |\mathbf{p} \cdot \mathbf{v}| \mathbf{v}.\]Then
\[\mathbf{y} = (3,6,15) - \frac{156}{15} (2,1,-2) = \boxed{\left( -3,-6,3 \right)}.\]

Let $P = (x,y,z),$ and let the vertices of the octahedron be $A = (a,0,0),$ $B = (-a,0,0),$ $C = (0,a,0),$ $D = (0,-a,0),$ $E = (0,0,a),$ and $F = (0,0,-a).$  Then the squares of the distances from $P$ to the vertices are
\begin{align*}
d_A^2 &= (x - a)^2 + y^2 + z^2, \\
d_B^2 &= (x + a)^2 + y^2 + z^2, \\
d_C^2 &= x^2 + (y - a)^2 + z^2, \\
d_D^2 &= x^2 + (y + a)^2 + z^2, \\
d_E^2 &= x^2 + y^2 + (z - a)^2, \\
d_F^2 &= x^2 + y^2 + (z + a)^2.
\end{align*}Note that
\[d_A^2 + d_B^2 = d_C^2 + d_D^2 = d_E^2 + d_F^2 = 2x^2 + 2y^2 + 2z^2 + 2a^2.\]Among the distances 3, 7, 8, 9, and 11, we check the sum of their squares in pairs:
\begin{align*}
3^2 + 7^2 &= 58, \\
3^2 + 8^2 &= 73, \\
3^2 + 9^2 &= 90, \\
3^2 + 11^2 &= 130, \\
7^2 + 8^2 &= 113, \\
7^2 + 9^2 &= 130, \\
7^2 + 11^2 &= 170, \\
8^2 + 9^2 &= 145, \\
8^2 + 11^2 &= 185, \\
9^2  + 11^2 &= 202.
\end{align*}We see only one repeated value, namely $3^2 + 11^2 = 7^2 + 9^2 = 130.$  Therefore, the sixth distance must be $\sqrt{130 - 8^2} = \boxed{\sqrt{66}}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
Let $O$ be the center of the octahedron and $Q$ be the midpoint of $\overline{OP}$. Since $\overline{CD},\overline{BE},\overline{AF}$ are perpendicular bisectors of $\overline{OP},$ line $EF$ passes through $Q.$ Therefore, by the Law of Cosines for triangle $ADQ$, $(AD/2)^2 + QD^2 - AD \cdot QD = PQ^2.$ Since $\overline{CD}$ is a diagonal of the octahedron, $CD^2=2QD^2,$ so $(AD/2)^2 + QD^2 - AD\cdot QD = PQ^2$ yields $$\left(\frac{AD}{2}\right)^2 + \frac{CD^2}{4}-\frac{AD\cdot CD}{4} = PQ^2.$$Since $\overline{CD}$ is also a side of the octahedron, $CD=2AF=\sqrt{2}\cdot AD,$ so we can simplify above to  $$\left(\frac{AD}{2}\right)^2 + \frac{AD^2}{4}-\frac{AD^2\sqrt{2}}{4} = PQ^2,$$which factors as $$\frac{AD^2}{8}(5-\sqrt{2}) = PQ^2.$$Therefore, if the distance from $P$ to the remaining vertex is $a,$ then $$\left(\frac{11^2+9^2+8^2+7^2+3^2+a^2}{6}\right)\cdot \frac{AD^2}{8}(5-\sqrt{2})=a^2,$$so $$a = \sqrt{\frac{8\cdot \left(\frac{11^2+9^2+8^2+7^2+3^2+a^2}{6}\right)}{5-\sqrt{2}}}.$$ We can now solve this equation for $a$ with, for instance, the bisection method, divide-and-conquer algorithm, or calculus. Alternatively, we can note that if $AD=2,$ then we seek the fifth positive solution of
\[\sqrt{\frac{1}{10}\left(121+81+64+49+9+a^2\right)}=\frac{\sqrt2}{2} \sqrt{\frac{5+\sqrt2}{8}}.\]Dividing both sides by $\sqrt{10}$ and squaring gives
\[a^2-\left(99+81+64+49+9\right)/10=4\cdot\frac{5-\sqrt2}{2\sqrt{10}}\cdot\frac{121+81+64+49+9+a^2}{60},\]which simplifies to \[a^2-44=20\sqrt{10}\cdot\frac{a^2+324}{2\cdot10\cdot\sqrt{10}+8\sqrt2};\]then \[(a^2-44)\left(2\cdot10\cdot\sqrt{10}+8\sqrt2\right)=20\sqrt{10}(a^2+324);\]so we can solve $\sqrt{320}(a^2+324)=9a^2-44\sqrt{2}$ using algebra. In any case, the value turns out to be $\boxed{2\sqrt{178}}.$

By product-to-sum,
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ} - 2 \sin 70^\circ &= \frac{1 - 4 \sin 10^\circ \sin 70^\circ}{2 \sin 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1 - 2 (\cos 60^\circ - \cos 80^\circ)}{2 \sin 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{2 \cos 80^\circ}{2 \sin 10^\circ} = \boxed{1}.
\end{align*}

Extracting Answer from: 
By the product-to-sum formula,
\[2 \sin 70^\circ \sin 10^\circ = \cos 60^\circ - \cos 80^\circ = \frac{1}{2} - \cos 80^\circ,\]so
\[\frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ} = \frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ} - 2 \sin 70^\circ + 2 \sin 70^\circ = \frac{1}{2} - \cos 80^\circ + 2 \sin 70^\circ.\]We know that $\sin 70^\circ = \cos 20^\circ,$ so
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ} - 2 \sin 70^\circ &= \frac{1}{2} - \cos 80^\circ + 2 \cos 20^\circ \\
&= \frac{1}{2} - 2 \sin^2 40^\circ + 2 \cos 20^\circ \\
&= \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1 - \cos 80^\circ}{2} + 2 \cos 20^\circ \\
&= \frac{\cos 80^\circ + 4 \cos 20^\circ}{2} \\
&= \cos 80^\circ + 2 \cos 20^\circ.
\end{align*}We have that
\[\cos 2x = 1 - 2 \sin^2 x,\]so
\[\cos 80^\circ = \cos (90^\circ - 10^\circ) = \sin 10^\circ = \cos 80^\circ,\]and
\begin{align*}
\cos 3x &= 4 \cos^3 x - 3 \cos x \\
&= 4 (2 \cos^2 x - 1)^2 - 3 (2 \cos^2 x - 1) \\
&= 8 \cos^4 x - 8 \cos^2 x + 1.
\end{align*}Letting $x = 10^\circ,$ we get
\[\cos 30^\circ = 8 \cos^4 10^\circ - 8 \cos^2 10^\circ + 1.\]Then $\cos^2 10^\circ$ satisfies the quadratic
\[8x^2 - 8x + 1 - \frac{1}{2} = 0.\]By the quadratic formula,
\[x = \frac{1 \pm \sqrt{2}}{4},\]so $2 \cos^2 10^\circ = 1 + \sqrt{2}$ or $2 \cos^2 10^\circ = 1 - \sqrt{2}.$  Since $\cos 20^\circ = 2 \cos^2 10^\circ - 1,$
\[2 \cos 20^\circ = \sqrt{2} - 1,\]so
\[\frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ} - 2 \sin 70^\circ = \boxed{\sqrt{2} - 1}.\]

Original File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/904.json
Extracting Answer from: 
We have that
\[\cos \theta = \frac{\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c})}{\|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|}.\]Let $d = \|\mathbf{a}\| = \|\mathbf{b}\| = \|\mathbf{c}\|.$  Since $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ $\mathbf{c}$ are mutually orthogonal, $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 0.$  Hence,
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = d^2.\]Also,
\begin{align*}
\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|^2 &= (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) \\
&= \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{c} + 2(\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c}) \\
&= d^2 + d^2 + d^2 \\
&= 3d^2.
\end{align*}Hence, $\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| = d \sqrt{3},$ so
\[\cos \theta = \frac{d^2}{d \cdot d \sqrt{3}} = \boxed{\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}}.\]

Stripped String:

Answer from Original: 1/(sqrt(3))

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/904_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
Since $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c}$ have equal magnitudes and any pair of them are orthogonal,
\[\|\mathbf{a}\| = \|\mathbf{b}\| = \|\mathbf{c}\| = k\]for some positive constant $k.$  We can write
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 + \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}).\]Note that since $\mathbf{a}$ is orthogonal to both $\mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{c},$ $\mathbf{a}$ is orthogonal to $\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}.$  Therefore, $\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 = k^2.$

Also,
\[\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| = \sqrt{(\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c})} = \sqrt{\|\mathbf{a}\|^2 + 2 \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) + \|\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|^2}.\]Note that
\[\|\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|^2 = (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) \cdot (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = \|\mathbf{b}\|^2 + 2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} + \|\mathbf{c}\|^2 = 2k^2.\]Also, as above, $\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = 0,$ so
\[\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|^2 = k^2 + 2 \cdot 0 + 2k^2 = 3k^2.\]Therefore,
\[\cos^2 \theta = \frac{(\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}))^2}{\|\mathbf{a}\|^2 \cdot \|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|^2} = \frac{k^4}{k^2 \cdot 3k^2} = \frac{1}{3}.\]Since the angle $\theta$ is acute, $\cos \theta = \boxed{\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}}.$

Since $\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}$ is orthogonal to both $\mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{c},$ $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = 0$ and $\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 0.$

Since $\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| = 1,$
\[(\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) \cdot (\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = 1.\]Expanding, we get
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} \cdot \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} + 2 \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} + 2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 1.\]From what we know, this becomes
\[\frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{6} + 0 + 0 + 2 \mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 1.\]Hence, $\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 0.$  This means the angle between $\mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{c}$ is $\boxed{90^\circ}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
We have that
\[\|\mathbf{a}\| = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},\]so
\[\|\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}\| = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2k^2}} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{|k|}.\]Also $\|\mathbf{b}\| = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}$ and $\|\mathbf{c}\| = \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}},$ so
\[\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| \le \|\mathbf{a}\| + \|\mathbf{b}\| + \|\mathbf{c}\| = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}.\]Squaring the given equation, we get
\[\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\|^2 = \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 + \|\mathbf{b}\|^2 + \|\mathbf{c}\|^2 + 2 \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{b}\| + 2 \|\mathbf{a}\| \|\mathbf{c}\| + 2 \|\mathbf{b}\| \|\mathbf{c}\|.\]Hence,
\[1 = \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{6} + 2 \| \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} \|.\]Also, $\|\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| \le \|\mathbf{b}\| + \|\mathbf{c}\| = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},$ so
\[\|\mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| = \|\mathbf{a}\| + \|\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| \ge \|\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}\| - \|\mathbf{a}\| = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}.\]This means
\[\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \le 2 \| \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} \| \le \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}.\]Solving, we find $\frac{\sqrt{2}}{4} \le \| \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} \| \le \frac{7 \sqrt{2}}{24}.$

Then $|k| = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\|\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}\|},$ so
\[\frac{1}{2 k^2} = \frac{1}{2} \|\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}\|^2 = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{2}{k^2},\]which means $k^2 = \frac{1}{2}.$  Hence, $|k| = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}},$ so without loss of generality, we can take $k = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}.$  Then
\[\mathbf{a} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}),\]so
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = 0.\]Then
\[\left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) (\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}) \cdot (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = 0.\]We can expand this as
\[\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} [\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}]^T (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} (\mathbf{b}^T \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{b}) = 0,\]so $\mathbf{b}^T \mathbf{c} = \mathbf{c}^T \mathbf{b}.$  Then $\mathbf{b}^T \mathbf{c} - \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \cdot \|\mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c}\| \cos A = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \cos A = \frac{1}{2} \cos A,$ where $A$ is the angle between $\mathbf{b}$ and $\mathbf{c}.$

Then
\[\cos A = \frac{2 \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} - \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} - \frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}.\]Finally, $\boxed{A = 30^\circ}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
We have that
\[\cos t = \cos \left( \frac{180t}{\pi} \right)^\circ.\]If the cosines of two angles (in degrees) are equal, either their difference is a multiple of $360^\circ,$ or their sum is a multiple of $360^\circ.$  Thus, $t + \frac{180t}{\pi} = 360^\circ k$ for $t - \frac{180t}{\pi} = 360^\circ k.$

From the first equation,
\[t = \frac{360^\circ \pi k}{\pi + 180}.\]The smallest positive real number of this form is $\frac{360 \pi}{\pi + 180}.$

From the second equation,
\[t = \frac{360^\circ \pi k}{\pi - 180}.\]The smallest positive real number of this form is $\frac{360 \pi}{180 - \pi}.$

Therefore, $t = \frac{360 \pi}{\pi + 180} \approx 6.175,$ so $\lfloor t \rfloor = \boxed{6}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
Converting $\cos \theta^\circ$ to radians, we get
\begin{align*}
\cos \theta^\circ &= \cos (\pi \theta/180) \\
&= \frac{e^{i \pi \theta/180} + e^{-i \pi \theta/180}}{2} \\
&= \frac{e^{i \pi \theta/180} + e^{i \cdot (-\pi) \theta/180}}{2} \\
&= \frac{e^{i \pi \theta/180} - e^{i \pi (\theta - 360)/180}}{2}.
\end{align*}Hence, we want $t$ to satisfy
\[0 < t < 360^\circ,\]and
\[\cos t = \cos t^\circ = \frac{e^{i \pi t/180} - e^{i \pi (t - 360)/180}}{2}.\]Then $\cos t \cdot 2 = e^{i \pi t/180} - e^{i \pi (t - 360)/180}.$  Writing $z = e^{i \pi t/180},$ we get
\[2 \cos t = z - z e^{-i 2 \pi/3}.\]Then $z^3 - 2 (\cos t) z^2 - z + 2 (\cos t) = 0.$  By the Intermediate Value Theorem, this equation has a root between $1$ and $2,$ so let $z_0$ be the smallest positive real root.  Then
\[\cos t = \frac{z_0^3 - z_0}{2 z_0^2 - 2}.\]Therefore, $z_0^3 - 2 (\cos t) z_0^2 - z_0 + 2 (\cos t) = 0.$  Then by the Intermediate Value Theorem, the smallest possible value of $\cos t$ is obtained when $t = \frac{289}{2},$ so $\lfloor t \rfloor = \boxed{144}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
We know that $\cot 9^\circ = \tan 81^\circ$ and $\cot 27^\circ = \tan 63^\circ,$ so
\[\tan 9^\circ + \cot 9^\circ - \tan 27^\circ - \cot 27^\circ = \tan 9^\circ + \tan 81^\circ - \tan 27^\circ - \tan 63^\circ.\]Then
\begin{align*}
\tan 9^\circ + \tan 81^\circ - \tan 27^\circ - \tan 63^\circ &= \tan 9^\circ - \tan 27^\circ + \tan 81^\circ - \tan 63^\circ \\
&= \frac{\sin 9^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ} - \frac{\sin 27^\circ}{\cos 27^\circ} + \frac{\sin 81^\circ}{\cos 81^\circ} - \frac{\sin 63^\circ}{\cos 63^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ - \sin 27^\circ \cos 9^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ} + \frac{\sin 81^\circ \cos 63^\circ - \sin 63^\circ \cos 81^\circ}{\cos 81^\circ \cos 63^\circ}.
\end{align*}From the angle subtraction formula,
\begin{align*}
&\frac{\sin 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ - \sin 27^\circ \cos 9^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ} + \frac{\sin 81^\circ \cos 63^\circ - \sin 63^\circ \cos 81^\circ}{\cos 81^\circ \cos 63^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\sin (9^\circ - 27^\circ)}{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ} + \frac{\sin (81^\circ - 63^\circ)}{\cos 81^\circ \cos 63^\circ} \\
&= -\frac{\sin 18^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ} + \frac{\sin 18^\circ}{\cos 81^\circ \cos 63^\circ} \\
&= \sin 18^\circ \cdot \frac{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ - \cos 63^\circ \cos 81^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ \cos 63^\circ \cos 81^\circ} \\
&= \sin 18^\circ \cdot \frac{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ - \sin 27^\circ \sin 9^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ \sin 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ \sin 27^\circ}.
\end{align*}From the angle addition formula and double angle formula,
\begin{align*}
\sin 18^\circ \cdot \frac{\cos 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ - \sin 27^\circ \sin 9^\circ}{\cos 9^\circ \sin 9^\circ \cos 27^\circ \sin 27^\circ} &= \sin 18^\circ \cdot \frac{\cos (27^\circ + 9^\circ)}{\frac{1}{2} \sin 18^\circ \cdot \frac{1}{2} \sin 54^\circ} \\
&= \frac{4 \sin 18^\circ \cos 36^\circ}{\sin 18^\circ \sin 54^\circ} \\
&= \boxed{4}.
\end{align*}

GPT File: 4-12-MATH-test-vanilla-answers/test/precalculus/answers/912_answer.json
Extracting Answer from: 
By the triple angle formula,
\begin{align*}
\tan 27^\circ &= \tan (3 \cdot 9^\circ) \\
&= \frac{3 \tan 9^\circ - \tan^3 9^\circ}{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ} \\
&= \frac{3 \tan 9^\circ - (\tan^2 9^\circ)(3 \sec^2 9^\circ - 1)}{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ} \\
&= \frac{3 \tan 9^\circ - 3 \tan^3 9^\circ + \tan^2 9^\circ}{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ}.
\end{align*}Also,
\[\cot 27^\circ = \frac{1}{\tan 27^\circ} = \frac{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ}{3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ}.\]Hence,
\begin{align*}
&\tan 9^\circ + \cot 9^\circ - \tan 27^\circ - \cot 27^\circ \\
&= \tan 9^\circ + \frac{1}{\tan 9^\circ} - \frac{3 \tan 9^\circ - 3 \tan^3 9^\circ + \tan^2 9^\circ}{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ} - \frac{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ}{3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\tan^2 9^\circ}{\tan 9^\circ} - \frac{3 \tan 9^\circ - 3 \tan^3 9^\circ + \tan^2 9^\circ}{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ} - \frac{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ}{3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ} \\
&= \frac{\tan^4 9^\circ - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ + 1}{\tan 9^\circ (1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ)} - \frac{1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ}{3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ}.
\end{align*}We could leave the expression as is; it is a perfectly fine form.  Another alternative is to continue to manipulate it until we obtain an expression in the form $\frac{p}{q}$ for some polynomials $p$ and $q$.

Subtracting the fractions in the expression above, we get
\begin{align*}
&\frac{\tan^4 9^\circ - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ + 1 - (\tan^2 9^\circ - 3 \tan^4 9^\circ + \tan^6 9^\circ + 3 \tan^2 9^\circ - \tan^4 9^\circ)}{\tan 9^\circ (1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ) (3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ)} \\
&= \frac{2 \tan^6 9^\circ - 6 \tan^4 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ + 1}{\tan 9^\circ (1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ) (3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ)}.
\end{align*}Then
\begin{align*}
&2 \tan^6 9^\circ - 6 \tan^4 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ + 1 \\
&= (2x - 1)(\tan^2 9^\circ - 1)^2 (2 \tan^2 9^\circ + 1).
\end{align*}Therefore,
\[\frac{2 \tan^6 9^\circ - 6 \tan^4 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ + 1}{\tan 9^\circ (1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ) (3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ)} = \frac{(2x - 1)(\tan^2 9^\circ - 1)^2 (2 \tan^2 9^\circ + 1)}{\tan 9^\circ (1 - 3 \tan^2 9^\circ) (3 \tan - \tan^3 9^\circ - \tan^2 9^\circ)}.\]Hence,
\[\tan 9^\circ + \cot 9^\circ - \tan 27^\circ - \cot 27^\circ = \boxed{(2x - 1)(\tan^2 9^\circ - 1)^2 (2 \tan^2 9^\circ + 1)}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
The equation for the $xy$-plane is $z = 0.$

[asy]
import three;
import solids;

size(300);
currentprojection = perspective(-2,-2,3);

draw((2,17,0)--(17,2,0)--(-8,-29,0)--(-29,-8,0)--cycle);
draw(shift((4,7,5))*surface(sphere(5)),gray(0.8));
draw(shift((-2,5,4))*surface(sphere(4)),gray(0.8));
draw(shift((2,1,4))*surface(sphere(4)),gray(0.8));
draw((2,17,6)--(17,2,6)--(-8,-29,-1)--(-29,-8,-1)--cycle);
draw((0,-29,0)--(-29,0,0));

label("$x + y = -29$", (0,-29,0), E);
[/asy]

Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 5 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix},$ $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix},$ and $\mathbf{c} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 7 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}.$  Then the normal vector to the plane passing through the centers of the spheres is
\[(\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}) \times (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}) = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -4 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 6 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -4 \\ -4 \\ 32 \end{pmatrix}.\]We can scale this vector, and take $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ -8 \end{pmatrix}$ as the normal vector.  Thus, the equation of the plane is of the form $x + y - 8z = d.$  Substituting any of the centers, we find the equation of this plane is
\[x + y - 8z = -29.\]The intersection of this plane with the plane $z = 0$ is the line defined by
\[x + y = -29.\]The equation of any plane containing this line is then of the form
\[kx + ky + z = -29k.\]We want all three spheres to be tangent to this plane.  Then the distance between this plane and the center $(-2,5,4)$ should be 4.  From the formula for the distance between a point and a plane,
\[\frac{|-2k + 5k + 4 + 29k|}{\sqrt{k^2 + k^2 + 1}} = 4.\]Then $|32k + 4| = 4 \sqrt{2k^2 + 1},$ so $|8k + 1| = \sqrt{2k^2 + 1}.$  Squaring, we get $64k^2 + 16k + 1 = 2k^2 + 1,$ which simplifies to
\[62k^2 + 16k = 2k(31k + 8) = 0.\]The solutions are $k = 0$ and $k = -\frac{8}{31}.$  The solution $k = 0$ corresponds to the plane $z = 0,$ so the other plane corresponds to $k = -\frac{8}{31},$ which gives us the equation
\[-\frac{8}{31} x - \frac{8}{31} y + z = 29 \cdot \frac{8}{31}.\]Thus, $\frac{c}{a} = \boxed{-\frac{31}{8}}.$

Extracting Answer from: 
We shift the coordinate system so that $A(-2, 5, 4),$ $B(2, 1, 4),$ and $C(4, 7, 5)$ are all tangent to the $xy$-plane at $(-2, 5, 0),$ $(2, 1, 0),$ and $(4, 7, 0),$ respectively.

[asy]
import three;

size(220);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);
defaultpen(linetype("8 8"));

triple I = (2,0,0), J = (0,2,0), K = (0,0,2), O = (0,0,0);
draw(surface(O--I--I+J--J--cycle),palegray,nolight);
draw(surface(O--I--I+K--K--cycle),palegray,nolight);
draw(surface(O--J--J+K--K--cycle),palegray,nolight);
draw((0,-1,0)--(0,8,0),black+linewidth(1.5),EndArrow(5));
draw((0,0,-1)--(0,0,6),black+linewidth(1.5),EndArrow(5));
draw((3,6,2)--(3,6,0),dashed);

triple A = (-2,5,4), B = (2,1,4), C = (4,7,5);
triple Ap = (-2,5,0), Bp = (2,1,0), Cp = (4,7,0);
triple[] dots = {A,B,C,Ap,Bp,Cp};

dot(dots);
draw(B--C--Cp--Bp--B);
draw(C--A--Ap--Cp--C,red);
draw(A--B--Bp--Ap--A);

label("$A$",A,1.5*NW,fontsize(8));
label("$B$",B,1.5*W,fontsize(8));
label("$C$",C,1.5*NE,fontsize(8));
label("$A'$",Ap,1.5*NW,fontsize(8));
label("$B'$",Bp,1.5*W,fontsize(8));
label("$C'$",Cp,1.5*NE,fontsize(8));
[/asy]

Note that the plane passing through $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ meets the $xy$-plane at $(-\sin \theta, \cos \theta, 0),$ $(\sin \theta, \cos \theta, 0),$ and $(\cos \phi, \sin \phi, 0)$ for some $0 \le \theta, \phi \le \frac{\pi}{2}.$

The spheres can be expressed as
\[(x + 2)^2 + (y - 5)^2 + (z - 4)^2 = r_1^2,\] \[(x - 2)^2 + (y - 1)^2 + (z - 4)^2 = r_2^2,\] and \[(x - 4)^2 + (y - 7)^2 + (z - 5)^2 = r_3^2.\] We translate to the $xy$-plane to get
\[(x + 2)^2 + (y - 5)^2 = r_1^2 - 4^2,\] \[(x - 2)^2 + (y - 1)^2 = r_2^2 - 4^2,\] and \[(x - 4)^2 + (y - 7)^2 = r_3^2 - 5^2.\] Let $d_1,$ $d_2,$ and $d_3$ be the distances from $A',$ $B',$ and $C'$ to the $xy$-plane.  Then
\begin{align*}
d_1^2 &= (r_1 - 4)^2 \\
d_2^2 &= (r_2 - 4)^2 \\
d_3^2 &= (r_3 - 5)^2.
\end{align*}

Let $O_1,$ $O_2,$ and $O_3$ be the centers of the three spheres.  Then $O_1A' = r_1,$ so $O_1A'^2 = r_1^2.$  Then $O_1$ lies on the sphere centered at $A,$ and the tangent point is $A'$ (the only point equidistant to $A$ and $O_1$).  Then by the Pythagorean theorem on right triangle $O_1A'A,$
\[OA = \sqrt{(O_1A')^2 + d_1^2} = \sqrt{r_1^2 + (r_1 - 4)^2}.\] By symmetry,
\[OB = \sqrt{(O_2B')^2 + d_2^2} = \sqrt{r_2^2 + (r_2 - 4)^2}\] and
\[OC = \sqrt{(O_3C')^2 + d_3^2} = \sqrt{r_3^2 + (r_3 - 5)^2}.\]

Now,
\begin{align*}
A'O_1^2 &= (r_1 - 4)^2 \\
B'O_2^2 &= (r_2 - 4)^2 \\
C'O_3^2 &= (r_3 - 5)^2,
\end{align*} so
\begin{align*}
d(O_1,O_2)^2 &= ||\overrightarrow{O_1O_2}||^2 \\
&= (OA + OB)^2 + (d_1 + d_2)^2 - (O_1A' + O_2B')^2 \\
&= (OA + OB)^2 + (d_1 + d_2)^2 - (r_1 + r_2)^2 + 32.
\end{align*}By symmetry, $d(O_1,O_3)^2 = (OA + OC)^2 + (d_1 + d_3)^2 - (r_1 + r_3)^2 + 50$ and $d(O_2,O_3)^2 = (OB + OC)^2 + (d_2 + d_3)^2 - (r_2 + r_3)^2 + 50.$  In other words,
\begin{align*}
[A,B,C] &= \begin{vmatrix}
d(O_1,O_2)^2 - 32 & d(O_1,O_3)^2 - 50 \\
d(O_2,O_3)^2 - 50 & d(O_1,O_2)^2 - 32
\end{vmatrix} \\
&= \left( \left[ OA^2 + OB^2 + 2 \cdot OA \cdot OB + d_1^2 + d_2^2 \right] - r_1^2 - r_2^2 - 2r_1r_2 \right) \cdot \left( \left[ OA^2 + OC^2 + 2 \cdot OA \cdot OC + d_1^2 + d_3^2 \right] - r_1^2 - r_3^2 - 2r_1r_3 \right) \\
&\quad - \left( d(O_1,O_2)^2 - 32 + 50 \right) \cdot \left( d(O_1,O_2)^2 - 32 + 50 \right) \\
&= \left( \left[ r_1^2 + r_2^2 + 2 \cdot \sqrt{r_1^2 + (r_1 - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{r_2^2 + (r_2 - 4)^2} + (r_1 - 4)^2 + (r_2 - 4)^2 \right] - r_1^2 - r_2^2 - 2r_1r_2 \right) \\
&\quad \cdot \left( \left[ r_1^2 + r_3^2 + 2 \cdot \sqrt{r_1^2 + (r_1 - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{r_3^2 + (r_3 - 5)^2} + (r_1 - 4)^2 + (r_3 - 5)^2 \right] - r_1^2 - r_3^2 - 2r_1r_3 \right) \\
&\quad - \left( \left[ r_1 + r_2 + 4 \right]^2 - 32 \right)^2 \\
&= \left[ 4 \sqrt{r_1^2 + (r_1 - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{r_2^2 + (r_2 - 4)^2} - 8r_1r_2 + 24r_1 + 24r_2 - 80 \right] \\
&\quad \cdot \left[ 2 \sqrt{r_1^2 + (r_1 - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{r_3^2 + (r_3 - 5)^2} - 2r_1r_3 - 52r_1 + 50r_3 - 441 \right] \\
&\quad - \left[ r_1 + r_2 + 4 \right]^4 + 64 \cdot \left[ r_1 + r_2 + 4 \right]^2.
\end{align*}Note that if $a = r_1,$ $b = r_2,$ and $c = r_3,$ then $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ are uniquely determined by the equations
\begin{align*}
a^2 + (a - 4)^2 &= (x + 2)^2 + (y - 5)^2 - 4^2, \\
b^2 + (b - 4)^2 &= (x - 2)^2 + (y - 1)^2 - 4^2, \\
c^2 + (c - 5)^2 &= (x - 4)^2 + (y - 7)^2 - 5^2,
\end{align*}respectively.  So it remains to find the product
\begin{align*}
P &= \left[ 4 \sqrt{a^2 + (a - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{b^2 + (b - 4)^2} - 8ab + 24a + 24b - 80 \right] \\
&\quad \cdot \left[ 2 \sqrt{a^2 + (a - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{c^2 + (c - 5)^2} - 2ac - 52a + 50c - 441 \right] \\
&\quad - \left[ a + b + 4 \right]^4 + 64 \cdot \left[ a + b + 4 \right]^2.
\end{align*}Let $x = a + b.$  Then
\begin{align*}
P &= \left[ 4 \sqrt{a^2 + (a - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{(x - a)^2 + (x - a - 4)^2} - 8a(x - a) + 24a + 24(x - a) - 80 \right] \\
&\quad \cdot \left[ 2 \sqrt{a^2 + (a - 4)^2} \cdot \sqrt{(x - c)^2 + (x - c - 5)^2} - 2ac - 52a + 50c - 441 \right] \\
&\quad - \left[ x + 4 \right]^4 + 64 \cdot \left[ x + 4 \right]^2.
\end{align*}Setting $\frac{c}{a} = k,$ we use Maple to factor:
\begin{align*}
P &= (2k^2 + 13k + 21) (2k^2 - 11k - 19) (2k + 9)^2 (2k - 1)^2 \\
&\quad (k^4 - 10k^3 - 53k^2 + 232k + 282) \\
&\quad (k^6 - 5k^5 - 26k^4 + 23k^3 + 20k^2 - 57k - 146).
\end{align*}We see that $2k^2 - 11k - 19$ has two positive roots.  One is $\frac{19}{4},$ so the other is $-2.$  However, for $k = -2,$ the system of equations
\begin{align*}
a^2 + (a - 4)^2 &= (x + 2)^2 + (y - 5)^2 - 4^2, \\
b^2 + (b - 4)^2 &= (x - 2)^2 + (y - 1)^2 - 4^2, \\
c^2 + (c - 5)^2 &= (x - 4)^2 + (y - 7)^2 - 5^2,
\end{align*}has no solutions, so  $2k^2 - 11k - 19$ must have only one positive root, namely $k = \boxed{\frac{19}{4}}.$

Let $\mathbf{a} = \overrightarrow{OA},$ $\mathbf{b} = \overrightarrow{OB},$ and $\mathbf{c} = \overrightarrow{OC}.$  Then
\[\overrightarrow{AB} = \overrightarrow{OB} - \overrightarrow{OA} = \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}.\]Similarly, $\overrightarrow{AC} = \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}$ and $\overrightarrow{BC} = \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b}.$  We then want to compute
\[\overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{BC} = \mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b}) = \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}.\][asy]
unitsize(2 cm);

pair A, B, C, O;

A = dir(100);
B = dir(200);
C = dir(340);
O = (0,0);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(O--A,Arrow(6));
draw(O--B,Arrow(6));
draw(O--C,Arrow(6));

label("$A$", A, A);
label("$B$", B, B);
label("$C$", C, C);
label("$O$", O, NE);
label("$\mathbf{a}$", A/2, SW);
label("$\mathbf{b}$", B/2, SE);
label("$\mathbf{c}$", C/2, SW);
[/asy]

Since $AC = 5,$ $AC^2 = 25.$  But
\begin{align*}
AC^2 &= \|\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}\|^2 \\
&= (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}) \cdot (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}) \\
&= \|\mathbf{c}\|^2 - 2 \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} + \|\mathbf{a}\|^2 \\
&= 2R^2 - 2 \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c},
\end{align*}where $R$ is the circumradius.  Hence,
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} = R^2 - \frac{AC^2}{2}.\]Similarly, we can prove that
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = R^2 - \frac{AB^2}{2}.\]Therefore,
\[\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b} = \left( R^2 - \frac{AC^2}{2} \right) - \left( R^2 - \frac{AB^2}{2} \right) = \frac{AB^2 - AC^2}{2} = \frac{3^2 - 5^2}{2} = \boxed{-8}.\]

Extracting Answer from: 
Let $D$ be the midpoint of $BC,$ and let $r$ be the circumradius of triangle $ABC.$  Since $\angle BAC = 180^\circ - \angle BDC,$
\[\cos A = -\cos \angle BDC.\]Then
\[\overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{BC} = \overrightarrow{OA} \cdot (\overrightarrow{OD} + \overrightarrow{DC}).\]As in Solution 1, $r = \frac{10 \sqrt{14}}{14}.$

[asy]
unitsize (0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, O;

B = (0,0);
A = (2.42,3.59);
C = (5,0);
D = (B + C)/2;
O = circumcenter(A,B,C);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--O);
draw(O--D);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$O$", O, E);
[/asy]

Then $\overrightarrow{OD} = \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{BC},$ so
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{BC} &= \overrightarrow{OA} \cdot (\overrightarrow{OD} + \overrightarrow{DC}) \\
&= \overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{OD} + \overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{DC} \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{BC} + R^2 \\
&= \frac{1}{2} |\overrightarrow{OA}| |\overrightarrow{BC}| \cos A + R^2.
\end{align*}Note that $R = \frac{BC}{2 \sin A}.$  Then
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{OA} \cdot \overrightarrow{BC} &= \frac{1}{2} |\overrightarrow{OA}| |\overrightarrow{BC}| \cos A + R^2 \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{14 \sqrt{14}}{5} \cdot 3 \cos A + \left( \frac{5}{2 \sin A} \right)^2 \\
&= \frac{21 \sqrt{14}}{5} \cos A + \frac{25}{4 \sin^2 A}.
\end{align*}Let $x = \cos A.$  Then we want to find $21 \sqrt{14} x + \frac{25}{4(1 - x^2)}.$  Note that $5^2 = 3^2 + 4^2,$ so $\triangle ABC$ is a right triangle.  Hence, $\cos A = \frac{3}{5}.$  Substituting, we get
\[21 \sqrt{14} \cdot \frac{3}{5} + \frac{25}{4 \cdot \frac{16}{25}} = \boxed{\frac{301 \sqrt{14}}{20}}.\]

Note that
\[\mathbf{A}^2 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 & 7 \\ -1 & -3 \end{pmatrix}\]and
\[\mathbf{A}^3 = \mathbf{A} \mathbf{A}^2 = \begin{pmatrix} -1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix} = -\mathbf{I}.\]Then
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{A}^{27} + \mathbf{A}^{31} + \mathbf{A}^{40} &= (\mathbf{A}^3)^9 + (\mathbf{A}^3)^{10} \mathbf{A} + (\mathbf{A}^3)^{13} \mathbf{A} \\
&= (-\mathbf{I})^9 + (-\mathbf{I})^{10} \mathbf{A} + (-\mathbf{I})^{13} \mathbf{A} \\
&= -\mathbf{I} + \mathbf{A} - \mathbf{A} \\
&= -\mathbf{I} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}}.
\end{align*}
